This is post terraform deploy, on all machines.
Folling the kubernetes docs.

Verify hostname, MAC address, and product_uuid are unique for every node
How:
  hostname  
  ip link 
  sudo cat /sys/class/dmi/id/product_uuid
Why:
  Kubernetes uses these values to uniquely identify the nodes in the cluster, if theyre not unique the install process
  may fail.

Check network adapters
How:
  ip route, check if we have a default route on the node network
Why: 
  We want Kubernetes node traffic to use the intended private interface and route. If a node has multiple adapters or the wrong default route, Kubernetes components may advertise or try to reach the wrong address.
Check that swap is off
How: 
  swapon --show
Why: 
  kubelet will fail to start if swap is on, unless we tolerate swap in kubelet configuration, which we are not gonna do, because we want memory pressure to be
  transparent

Check required ports
  Why:
  Kubernetes components need specific ports to communicate. In Kubing, these should be allowed privately between nodes, not exposed publicly.

  How:
  - Confirm the AWS security group allows node-to-node traffic inside the private cluster network/security group.
  - Confirm public inbound stays limited to SSH from my client IP.
  - Do not expect Kubernetes ports like 6443 to be open before kubeadm init.
  - Use nc later only when validating or debugging a running component.

Installing a container runtime
  How:
    Follow these steps:

    Enable IPv4 packet forwarding
      How:
        # sysctl params required by setup, params persist across reboots
        cat <<EOF | sudo tee /etc/sysctl.d/k8s.conf
        net.ipv4.ip_forward = 1
        EOF
        # Apply sysctl params without reboo
        sudo sysctl --system

        Then verify:
        sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward
        Should be = 1
      Why:
        Enable IPv4 forwarding because Kubernetes/CNI networking requires the node to forward traffic that did not originate from the node itself, such as Pod-to-Pod and Pod-to-external traffic.
      
    Install containerd
      How:
        # Add Docker's official GPG key:
        sudo apt update
        sudo apt install ca-certificates curl
        sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
        sudo curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.asc
        sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.asc

        # Add the repository to Apt sources:
        sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.sources <<EOF
        Types: deb
        URIs: https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu
        Suites: $(. /etc/os-release && echo "${UBUNTU_CODENAME:-$VERSION_CODENAME}")
        Components: stable
        Architectures: $(dpkg --print-architecture)
        Signed-By: /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.asc
        EOF

        sudo apt update
        #then install containerd
        sudo apt install containerd.io

        sudo vim /etc/containerd/config.toml

        Ensure the containerd 2.x runc runtime options contain:

        [plugins.'io.containerd.cri.v1.runtime'.containerd.runtimes.runc.options]
          SystemdCgroup = true
        
        Note:

        If you installed containerd from a package (for example, RPM or .deb), 
        you may find that the CRI integration plugin is disabled by default.
        So we need to delete that line from the config.toml

        sudo systemctl restart containerd
        sudo systemctl status containerd --no-pager

        containerd --version
        sudo grep -n "SystemdCgroup" /etc/containerd/config.toml
        sudo grep -n "disabled_plugins" /etc/containerd/config.toml
        ls -l /run/containerd/containerd.sock

      Why:
        Kubernetes needs a CRI-compatible container runtime. Kubing uses containerd. Docker's apt repository is only used as the package source for
        containerd.io; Kubernetes is not using Docker Engine. 
        why SystemdCgroup?
        Two cgroup managers result in two views of the available and in-use resources in the system.
        In some cases, nodes that are configured to use cgroupfs for the kubelet and container runtime, but use systemd for the rest of the processes become unstable under resource pressure.

    Installing kubeadm, kubelet and kubectl:
      How: 
    Update the apt package index and install packages needed to use the Kubernetes apt repository:

    sudo apt-get update
    # apt-transport-https may be a dummy package; if so, you can skip that package
    sudo apt-get install -y apt-transport-https ca-certificates curl gpg

    Download the public signing key for the Kubernetes package repositories. The same signing key is used for all repositories so you can disregard the version in the URL:

    # If the directory `/etc/apt/keyrings` does not exist, it should be created before the curl command, read the note below.
    # sudo mkdir -p -m 755 /etc/apt/keyrings
    curl -fsSL https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.36/deb/Release.key | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/kubernetes-apt-keyring.gpg

    Note:
    In releases older than Debian 12 and Ubuntu 22.04, directory /etc/apt/keyrings does not exist by default, and it should be created before the curl command.

    Add the appropriate Kubernetes apt repository. Please note that this repository have packages only for Kubernetes 1.36; for other Kubernetes minor versions, you need to change the Kubernetes minor version in the URL to match your desired minor version (you should also check that you are reading the documentation for the version of Kubernetes that you plan to install).

    # This overwrites any existing configuration in /etc/apt/sources.list.d/kubernetes.list
    echo 'deb [signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/kubernetes-apt-keyring.gpg] https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.36/deb/ /' | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/kubernetes.list

    Update the apt package index, install kubelet, kubeadm and kubectl, and pin their version:

    sudo apt-get update
    sudo apt-get install -y kubelet kubeadm kubectl
    sudo apt-mark hold kubelet kubeadm kubectl
    kubeadm version
    kubelet --version
    kubectl version --client
    apt-mark showhold

    (Optional) Enable the kubelet service before running kubeadm:

    sudo systemctl enable --now kubelet

    Before kubeadm init/join, kubelet may not become healthy yet because it has not received its cluster configuration. That is expected.


